<div id="outline-container-org5d4cfc0" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org5d4cfc0">11-jan, course: NLP,  overview and the main tasks</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org5d4cfc0">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>For the linguistic part you can refer to <a href="https://faculty.washington.edu/ebender/100things-sem_prag.html">https://faculty.washington.edu/ebender/100things-sem_prag.html</a></li>
<li>For the NLP basics: <a href="https://web.stanford.edu/~jurafsky/slp3/">https://web.stanford.edu/~jurafsky/slp3/</a></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org127d560" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org127d560">18-jan, course: Text classification</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org127d560">
<p>
The basics and a first NNet with W2V
</p>

<p>
Further and essential readings: 
</p>
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a href="http://www.jmlr.org/papers/volume12/collobert11a/collobert11a.pdf">Natural Language Processing (Almost) from Scratch</a></li>
<li><a href="http://www.jmlr.org/papers/volume3/bengio03a/bengio03a.pdf">A Neural Probabilistic Language Model</a></li>
<li><a href="http://u.cs.biu.ac.il/~yogo/nnlp.pdf">A Primer on Neural Network Models for Natural Language Processing</a></li>
</ul>

<p>
For word2vec and fasttext: 
</p>
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1310.4546">the original paper</a></li>
<li><a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1402.3722">word2vec explained</a></li>
<li><a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1607.04606">fasttext</a></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>



<div id="outline-container-org2afd313" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org2afd313">25-jan, course: sequence models</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org2afd313">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Language modelling</li>
<li>ngram language model</li>
<li>recurrent model</li>
</ul>

<p>
Some interesting readings: 
</p>
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a href="https://www.jmlr.org/papers/volume3/bengio03a/bengio03a.pdf">The seminal paper on ngram neural language model</a></li>
<li><a href="https://www.jmlr.org/papers/volume13/gutmann12a/gutmann12a.pdf">The long paper on Noise Contrastive Estimation (NCE)</a></li>
<li>and its <a href="https://www.cs.toronto.edu/~amnih/papers/ncelm.pdf">application to language modelling</a></li>
<li><a href="http://www.projectsgoal.com/download_projects/natural-language-processing/natural-language-processing-projects-GNLP00074.pdf">LSTM language models</a></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>


